    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras face a challenging slate today, exacerbated by significant weather-related absences. With **Trea Turner**, **Yordan Alvarez**, and **Kyle Schwarber** sidelined due to rainouts, our offensive ceiling is lower than usual. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (76.26) and **Junior Caminero** (74.22) anchor our lineup today, representing the strongest plays on the board. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** benefits from an elite matchup against a struggling pitcher in Waldron (7.83 xERA), with his speed profile making him an essential start to chase the scarce SB category. **Junior Caminero** remains a priority start; his position in the #2 hole combined with a solid 4.35 xERA matchup provides the best base-production floor among our healthy starters.\n\nWe have a cluster of players in the 60-point range, including **Hyeseong Kim** (61.99) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (61.17). **Hyeseong Kim** is a notable start thanks to favorable wind conditions (+5%) providing a lift to his power potential against Alcantara. Conversely, the most difficult bench decision involved **Dillon Dingler** (33.15). While he occupies the C2 spot for depth, he fell well below our 40-point efficiency floor due to a brutal matchup against Ritchie (2.57 xERA) and a poor platoon split, confirming the optimizer\u2019s decision to keep him on the bench to preserve game caps. \n\nManagers should remain wary of the bottom of the order. **Caleb Durbin** (47.42) and **Colt Keith** (46.51) are essentially \"marginal\" starts today. **Colt Keith** is particularly concerning; despite his lineup position, he is facing Ritchie, who is arguably the most dominant pitcher we are seeing today (2.57 xERA), dragging his score down significantly through a -19% SP skill adjustment. We are effectively punting on high-end production from these slots, hoping **Gary Sanchez** (59.37) or **Luke Raley** (58.78) can provide the necessary punch to keep our weekly totals competitive while we wait for **Trea Turner** and the others to return to the active lineup.",
